<hl>
<seg id=1> Japanese Prime Minister Hopes Miyazawa Will Not Quit, Instead Pursue Economic Recovery Program </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (REUTERS WIRE Tokyo) Japanese finance minister Kiichi Miyazawa was pressured  yesterday not to quit his post. </seg>
<seg id=3> Last week he announced that he was considering resigning soon. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> The question of Miyazawa's intentions has cast a shadow on the coalition government of Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi's Liberal Democratic Party and Ichiro Ozawa's Liberal Party. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> With the divergence of opinion surfacing among high officials about the issue of whether Liberal Party cabinet posts are in the agreement, the coalition government is beginning to look unstable. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> It is widely believed by those outside the party that should Miyazawa resign he would be replaced by Liberal Party secretary-general Noda. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Last Friday Miyazawa said that he might resign his position before the end of the year, but he didn't give a precise date. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> At the press conference he said, "I can't say when." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> It is expected he will act as finance minister until the end of the two-week special session of parliament. </seg>
<seg id=10> The session of parliament ends December 14. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> Keizo Obuchi's internal cabinet secretary Suzuki told Japan Broadcasting Corporation that he believes the prime minister wishes the 79 year-old Miyazawa not to resign his post. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> Suzuki said, "I think (Obuchi) secretly hopes he will remain at his position to carry out an economic recovery program." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=13> Obuchi will be meeting with Miyazawa. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=14> He said, "In terms of his ability, finding someone to replace him won't be easy. </seg>
<seg id=15> I myself hope he will stay to work toward re-energizing the country's economy." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=16> In regard to the public debate over Miyazawa's potential resignation, Obuchi has seen the reports, and plans to speak with the finance minister. </seg>
</p>
